commentBody:
@SamCorbin,  I loved your column, and like you,  I inexplicably made a big chore out of the NW with false starts like "debit" and " go up NORTH" (duh!).  I was finally able to find an arrangement allowing Diana RIGG , forever Emma Peel.

 I'd never heard of or been blessed with a Bottomless Brunch, but when I got it, I was delighted that all the "too long " answers  included brunch food!    Very cute !  
Fun solve!

@Megan,

Hello! For the record, my handle comes from traveling *from* Boulder to NYC. I was there for months at a time for a number of years, and I miss it terribly.  I’ve actually had Boulder as my primary residence since 1981. Confusing, I know.  

You’re right, the Dushanbe Teahouse is a real treasure.

@Robco 

I knew both RPG and REY, but I feel you: that would have been a horrible section of the puzzle for me if I were not a gamer and SW fan.

With the EEL at least the clue was fresh, for one of the stalest crossword words.

@Stewkak

I hadn't heard of them either, but:

<a href="https://skiboards.com" target="_blank">https://skiboards.com</a>/

@Jane The word "informally" tends to apply to common shorthand or slang — so it *can* be an abbreviation, but it doesn't have to be. For instance: [L.A.'s region, informally] is SOCAL, rather than Southern California. [Credit, informally] is PROPS. 

"For short" or "in brief" are more often indications of formalized abbreviations and initialisms, whether or not you'd say them aloud. [Annual presidential speech] is SOTU; [Crazy, sexy or cool] solves to ADJ, as in adjective.

But, as others have said, exceptions to this rule appear later in the week! Sometimes you've just got to plug things in until one fits.

@LARRY The theme is the whole reason the puzzle was designed as it was from the start. It's not a case of a puzzle not working out so let's just leave out a letter or add more letters in. 

There are six symmetrically-placed theme entries plus the central grid-spanning (16 letter!) revealer that explains the concept perfectly.

I can't imagine seeing someone created a puzzle like this and thinking that something just didn't fit and the constructor should have just tried harder.

@ElroyMcDaniels 

Contact the Games staff; they're very accommodating when it comes to glitches and streaks. 

That said, I had no problem in that area, so you may well have inadvertently entered a zero...

@Pani Korunova 

I think it’s pretty obvious what it is, but like Rich, I’ve never heard of that phrase in the wild. And between the two of us, that’s about a century and a half of unawareness. 

That doesn’t mean it doesn’t exist, but it seems a little obscure to be the tentpole of a puzzle.

@J 
I believe the clue doesn't reference snowboards (which use only one) but are what we used to call snowblades, which are very short skis that you can use to do tricks, among other things. They were a fad in the early 2000s - my nephews used them for a few years. And they do come in pairs. 
Just Google "skiboards" if you want to see an example.

@Heg 
Get up on the wrong side of the be?



If you can’t think of anything nic.

@Lewis 

I can relate. That happens to me a lot and I've learned to rely on it. I guess it's because our minds drift to different places in the course of solving the puzzle and maybe we just happen to be in the right place when we go back and look again. Oh - and of course there's also the magic of 'one crossing letter.' I'm amazed at how often that's enough to have something dawn on me. 

....

@William 

What brunch item do you have if you add a letter to the last part of BADEG?

(I assume you don't recognize the colloquial term that results by doing so, but it's definitely a thing.)

@William 

I was on the verge of asking the same question about BADEG. If I ever ate breakfast or brunch I'd probably have been a bit quicker to see the "egg" reference 
"Bad egg" feels very British English to me. Is it a common phrase in the US?

@Oikofuge

I'm pretty sure I was first introduced to the metaphor by Gene Wilder. Veruca, while British, was definitely not a "good egg".

<a href="https://youtube.com/watch?v=4EF1zYFHbus" target="_blank">https://youtube.com/watch?v=4EF1zYFHbus</a>

@JB,

It could have applied to the opposite, as well — getting a fertilized egg in a carton from the store. Very occasionally would a fertilized egg get through the candling process and be included in the carton. 

Of course, nothing inside was developed. A bit unpleasant when broken, but not traumatic.

@G 
"You're a good egg, Noonan."
(From Caddyshack.)

@Michael 

"With a thoughtless theme" gives you away.  You simply missed the theme, and perhaps are not up to the challenge.

Which is OK, one can improve, but that fact is not the puzzle's fault.

@Barry Ancona

Just a misspelling.

No need to mock.

@RozzieGrandma 
I had the same experience, Tuesday a delightful breeze, but Wednesday's was definitely rocky.  I was trudging along, hoping to avoid a cheat.  But I got 'felled' by what was surprisingly a Sports! question, "received a card, say".   I didn't know they notified one of fouls by sending a card?

(I love both novels and non-fiction.  Best are the bios that read like a novel.  I love the 'read and listen'.)

@RozzieGrandma 
I refused to renew AARP after they hooked up with United Health to peddle an Advantage Plan.  Rip-offs!  Basically, it's farming people to earn as much as they can by controlling whom you see for care, what drugs you can take, etc.  For Profit!!!!  shame on them.

I read both (currently The Power Broker--Caro's Pulitzer of 50 yrs ago; and just finished 5 Tana French mysteries.  Casting about for my next good read, and rereading a Frederik Backman novel.)

@Norman 
Only if you are divergent....

Wink!

@Carole 
Just to clarify, the Oona in GOT is the granddaughter of the Oona in the crosswords, who was the daughter of Eugene O'Neill and married Charlie Chaplin.

To be honest, I was so engrossed by the amazing and ever-changing animation in the GOT titles that I didn't usually notice the cast members' names.

@Mean Old Lady 

REY is the granddaughter of Emperor Palpatine, but was abandoned by her parents on a remote planet because they knew they were about to be killed by Palpatine's minions.

She was discovered/“rescued” by Rebel forces and developed Jedi-like abilities, and had a hate/love attraction with Han & Leia’s son Ben (Kylo Ren). Eventually faced her grandfather in the climactic scene of the ninth movie.

@Scott 

That boat has sailed, sadly. I worked for a year in various places across Canada, and so have been supervised through various iterations of brunch by various solicitous and kindly Canadians.
It didn't take.

@Bob T. 
Not a big fan of either the northern or southern version of chicken and waffles.
But this is getting a bit open-ended, isn't it?

@Steve L 

Strangely, one eats nothing but entrées at BOTTOMLESS BRUNCH, and so one can never leave.

Sort of like the Hotel California.

@Desert Dweller 
I would have thought that most people had heard the phrase, if nowhere else, at least once in a rather well-known movie:

<a href="https://youtube.com/watch?v=cwdCegstyR0" target="_blank">https://youtube.com/watch?v=cwdCegstyR0</a>

@Xword Junkie Clearly the puzzle wreaked havoc with my ability to use proper grammar.

Had "I'd not" and didn't pay attention when I hurriedly decided to replace "not" with "wouldn't".

Rushing to post a comment with a class to teach in three minutes probably contributed as well.

@Andy A bit harsh, I think. 

ENS: phonetic spellings of letters are fairly common in these puzzles (I have learnt this the hard way!), AGER is not a nonsense word, but the characters you have to add to the word in the clue to make another word or phrase, DEL: makes up a common key sequence to reboot your computer.

I'm with you on CSA and LAA though - absolutely no clue!

@Scott 
Good for you for hanging in there.
OBI is frequently in the crossword, so it is worth remembering.   I'm sure it's a gimme for most longtime solvers.

@Caro H 

Hi there, fellow New Englander.  Patti Varol over at LA Times does a great job editing their crossword puzzles--similar in difficulty to those here but without this kind of trickiness--at least in my experience.  And they are free!

Intending this comment to be helpful...I am also looking forward to Fri/Sat!

@festy

